<paragraph id="FA743E616E2040A5A27FACE31046FCD3" pageId="777" pageNumber="778">
<taxonomicName id="0867D6E8EDB3F8682B6856474B9CC82A" authorityName="Casey" authorityYear="1920" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Trapezodera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="777" pageNumber="778" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Trapezodera</taxonomicName>
Casey, 1920: 19. Type species: 
<taxonomicName id="21174D02B0EE0F750135C7F53CB0BB21" authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1891" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Colpodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="777" pageNumber="778" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aeneicauda">
<emphasis id="B9BD83972E2156A89F9AEE03D41168FB" italics="true" pageId="777" pageNumber="778">Colpodes aeneicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Bates, 1891 by original designation. Etymology. From the Greek 
<emphasis id="0FA90382E0451636FFD725582C31B52F" italics="true" pageId="777" pageNumber="778">trapezion</emphasis>
(an irregular four-shaped figure, by extension trapezoid) and 
<emphasis id="BA260CA532909154856E2A7AC1462183" italics="true" pageId="777" pageNumber="778">dere</emphasis>
(neck, by extension pronotum), alluding to the shape of the pronotum (&quot;trapezoidal outline of the prothorax&quot;) of the adult [feminine].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CD41799FAA960BF7CB170B7DC3C16152" pageId="777" pageNumber="778" type="diversity">
<paragraph id="98D8E7A4A17136EDDA31B7C8E2114265" pageId="777" pageNumber="778">Diversity.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="24DF02916DD2D31A0DE7D72104A38D82" pageId="777" pageNumber="778">Four species are assigned to this subgenus, one from southwestern United States and three from Mexico (Liebherr and Will 1996: 316).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
